# Perspective Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p2c4qe"
character
trait
=
single action
```

or:

```text id="u7c1qe"
point of view
=
author opinion
```

Some may:

```text id="c9c5qe"
assume
all characters
know
same information
```

without understanding:

```text id="k4c8qe"
point of view
shapes
understanding
```

Example:

text says:

```text id="n6c3qe"
Emma shared
her lunch
with a classmate
```

students may say:

```text id="t1c7qe"
Emma
is nice
because
one action
```

without asking:

```text id="q5c2qe"
what repeated
evidence
shows
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="v8c4qe"
perspective-based reading
```

For Grade 4:

focus includes:

Character:

* traits
* motivations
* feelings
* actions
* change over time

Point of View:

* narrator perspective
* first person
* third person
* different viewpoints
* evidence from text

Important distinction:

```text id="a9c1qe"
character
=
person in story

point of view
=
who sees
or tells
events
```

